# Callisto Backend — Local Runbook

Daily local setup for **`callisto-back-end`** on **`main`**. Use this repo branch for local work; feature branches are not required once changes are on `main`.

## Prerequisites

- **Node.js** 22+ (24 recommended per repo README)
- **Docker Desktop** running
- **GitHub PAT** with `read:packages`, SSO-authorized for PlanetDepos (`GITHUB_TOKEN` env var or in `.npmrc`)
- **AWS credentials** from [Planet Portal](https://planetportal.awsapps.com/start/#/?tab=accounts) when exercising S3/SQS (refresh session tokens often)
- **DBeaver** (or any Postgres client) for browsing the local database

## One-time setup

### 1. Clone, checkout `main`, install

```powershell
cd C:\Users\dustin.thomason\callisto-back-end
git checkout main
git pull origin main
npm ci
```

### 2. Local env files

Nest loads **`.env.local`** when `NODE_ENV=local` (see `src/config/config.module.options.ts`).

```powershell
Copy-Item .env.sample .env
Copy-Item .env.sample .env.local
$env:NODE_ENV = "local"
```

Edit **`.env.local`** for your machine. Typical local values:

| Variable | Local value |
| -------- | ----------- |
| `APP_PORT` | `3005` (or any free port) |
| `READ_DB_HOST` / `WRITE_DB_HOST` | `localhost` |
| `DB_PORT` | `5432` |
| `DB_NAME` | `callisto` |
| `DB_SCHEMA` | `callisto` |
| `DB_USERNAME` / `DB_PASSWORD` | `postgres` / `postgres` |
| `ENV_NAME` | `local` |
| `MQ_BROKER_URL` | `amqp://localhost:5672` |
| `MQ_USERNAME` / `MQ_PASSWORD` | `guest` / `guest` |

Keep **`DB_*`** values aligned in **`.env`** as well — the TypeORM CLI loads `.env` via `dotenv/config`, not `.env.local`.

Add fresh AWS keys to `.env.local` when you need S3/SQS. For messaging-only local runs, `OUTBOX_ENABLED=true` requires RabbitMQ (see below).

## Every session — start infrastructure

`docker compose up` in this repo only starts the **app** container, not PostgreSQL. Use the existing local containers instead.

### PostgreSQL (required)

```powershell
docker start callisto-postgres
docker ps --filter "name=callisto-postgres"
```

Expected: `callisto-postgres` is **Up** and maps `0.0.0.0:5432->5432/tcp`.

If the container does not exist yet (first machine only):

```powershell
docker run -d --name callisto-postgres `
  -e POSTGRES_USER=postgres `
  -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=postgres `
  -e POSTGRES_DB=callisto `
  -p 5432:5432 postgres:16
```

Create the schema once:

```powershell
docker exec callisto-postgres psql -U postgres -d callisto -c "CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS callisto;"
```

### RabbitMQ (required when `OUTBOX_ENABLED=true`)

```powershell
docker start callisto-rabbitmq
```

If the container does not exist yet:

```powershell
docker run -d --name callisto-rabbitmq `
  -p 5672:5672 -p 15672:15672 rabbitmq:3-management
```

Management UI: http://localhost:15672 (default login `guest` / `guest`).

Bootstrap **vhosts and exchanges** Callisto expects (`nova`, `callisto`). A plain `rabbitmq:3-management` container only has the `/` vhost; without this step you will see `Connection Failed ... broker (nova)` / `(callisto)` when `OUTBOX_ENABLED=true`:

```powershell
cd C:\Users\dustin.thomason\callisto-back-end
npm run setup:local-rabbitmq
```

Wait ~10 seconds after starting RabbitMQ before starting the API, or **restart the API** after running the bootstrap if broker connection warnings already appeared in logs.

## Migrations (Windows-safe command)

`npm run migration:run` can fail on Windows because TypeORM does not resolve `src/*` path aliases. Use:

```powershell
cd C:\Users\dustin.thomason\callisto-back-end
$env:NODE_ENV = "local"
npx ts-node -r dotenv/config -r tsconfig-paths/register ./node_modules/typeorm/cli.js migration:run -d ./src/typeorm/data-source.ts
```

Expected: `No migrations are pending`.

Migrations also run automatically on API startup when none are pending.

## Seed test data (optional)

```powershell
$env:NODE_ENV = "local"
npm run migration:seed
```

## Start the API

```powershell
cd C:\Users\dustin.thomason\callisto-back-end
$env:NODE_ENV = "local"
npx nest start --watch
```

Or with formatted logs:

```powershell
npm run dev:watch:pretty
```

### Verify

| Check | URL |
| ----- | --- |
| Health | http://localhost:3005/callisto/health |
| Swagger | http://localhost:3005/callisto/swagger |

Replace `3005` with your `APP_PORT` if different.

```powershell
curl.exe http://localhost:3005/callisto/health
```

Expected: HTTP 200, `"status":"ok"`.

## DBeaver — connect to local Callisto Postgres

Use these settings for a new **PostgreSQL** connection in DBeaver.

| Field | Value |
| ----- | ----- |
| Host | `localhost` |
| Port | `5432` |
| Database | `callisto` |
| Username | `postgres` |
| Password | `postgres` |

**Driver properties (optional):** none required for local Docker Postgres.

### After connecting

1. Open **SQL Editor** for the `callisto` connection.
2. Set the search path so tables resolve without schema prefix:

```sql
SET search_path TO callisto, public;
```

3. Browse tables under **Schemas → callisto** in the Database Navigator.

### Useful starter queries

```sql
-- Confirm schema and migration state
SET search_path TO callisto, public;
SELECT * FROM migrations ORDER BY id DESC LIMIT 5;

-- Row counts (after seed or manual data)
SELECT
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM cases) AS cases,
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM jobs) AS jobs,
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM files) AS files;
```

### DBeaver tips

- **Show all schemas:** Database Navigator → connection → Edit → PostgreSQL → check "Show all databases" / expand **Schemas** if tables look empty.
- **Default schema:** In connection settings → **PostgreSQL** tab → set **Default schema** to `callisto` to avoid running `SET search_path` every session.
- **SSL:** Off for local Docker (`localhost`).

## Atlas front-end (Jerry's local workflow)

Keep `atlas-front-end/.env.local` exactly as provided — do **not** uncomment backend URL lines unless you intentionally want to hit SB.

| `CALLISTO_API_URL` in `.env.local` | Callisto traffic goes to |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| **Commented out** (default for local UI + local Callisto) | `localhost` (Quasar dev proxy default: `http://localhost:3003`) |
| **Uncommented** → `https://atlas-sb.planetdepos.com` | Sandbox Callisto |

Triton and Europa stay pointed at SB in `.env.local` (`TRITON_API_URL`, `EUROPA_API_URL`) so you can run UI locally while those APIs stay on sandbox — easy to verify and test against real SB data.

Start Atlas:

```powershell
cd C:\Users\dustin.thomason\atlas-front-end
npm run dev:local
```

That sets `ENV_NAME=local` and loads `.env.local`. App: http://localhost:9000

**Toggle pattern:** local Callisto → leave `# CALLISTO_API_URL= ...` commented. Test UI against SB Callisto → uncomment that line.

